0.2 Data Overview

This section provides a structured summary of the dataset, including the number of records, key variables, and potential limitations. Understanding the datasets structure is critical for assessing the feasibility of future analyses, including the planned A/B test power calculations.

0.2.1 Dataset Summary

The dataset contains test records for Grade 11 students from Indias Jawahar Navodaya Vidyalayas (JNVs). These students are part of different academic streams (Engineering, Medical, and PCMB) and programs (e.g., JNV Nodal, JNV CoE). The dataset captures students test performance, school details, and academic classifications.

The dataset consists of:

  • 17,685 total records

  • 945 unique students

  • 23 schools

  • 274 unique test instances

  • 123 unique test types

These statistics provide an initial sense of scale and coverage.

0.2.3 Data Completeness & Quality

To ensure the datasets reliability, we checked for missing values, duplicates, and outliers. Our analysis confirms that the dataset is complete and well-structured, with no major data quality concerns.

Key findings:

  • No missing values in percentage (test scores).
  • No missing values in academic_level (student classification).
  • No duplicate student-test records detected.

This high level of data completeness strengthens confidence in subsequent analyses. While missing data is not a concern, we will still examine distribution patterns and potential outliers in later sections to validate the datasets integrity.

0.3.1 Distribution of Test Scores

0.3.1.1 Chapter tests

First, lets examine chapter test performance. Male students took 6,225 tests, while female students took 5,859. The average scores were 31.6% for males and 31.6% for females.

The score distributions for both genders are highly similar, with closely aligned peaks indicating comparable modal scores. The mean and median scores, marked by dashed and solid vertical lines, respectively, are nearly identical for males (31.6%) and females (31.6%). However, female students show slightly higher density in lower score ranges, while male scores are marginally more dispersed. Given the large sample sizes6225 for males and 5859 for femalesthese differences are unlikely to be driven by sample variability. Overall, gender differences in chapter test performance appear minimal, with no clear systematic bias favoring one group.

0.3.2 Mock tests

Next, lets examine mock test performance. Male students took 428 tests, while female students took 370. The average scores were 21.6% for males and 21.5% for females.

The score distributions for both genders reveal a highly similar performance pattern, with closely aligned peaks indicating comparable modal scores. The mean and median scores, marked by dashed and solid vertical lines, respectively, are nearly identical for males (31.6%) and females (31.6%). However, female students show slightly higher density in the lower score ranges, while male scores appear more dispersed, suggesting a broader distribution of performance among male students.

Given the large sample sizes6225 mock tests taken by males and 5859 by femalesthese differences are unlikely to be driven by sample variability. Overall, gender differences in mock test performance appear minimal, with no clear systematic bias favoring one group over the other.

Finally, lets examine major test performance. Male students took 2,545 tests, while female students took 2,258. The average scores were 22.7% for males and 20.9% for females.

The score distributions for both genders reveal a highly similar performance pattern, with closely aligned peaks indicating comparable modal scores. The mean and median scores, marked by dashed and solid vertical lines, respectively, are nearly identical for males (31.6%) and females (31.6%). 0.5 Dates

0.5.1 Timing of Tests

The distribution of test administration over the academic year reveals substantial variation in test frequency by month and test type.

  • Chapter tests (red) are heavily concentrated between July and October, with the largest spike occurring in August, when over 6,241 tests were administered. There is a sharp decline in chapter tests after October, with only minimal activity in November and December.
  • Major tests (green) are more evenly spread throughout the year, with relatively stable numbers observed from January to November. However, they peak slightly in July and October, aligning with the increased testing period seen for chapter tests.
  • Mock tests (blue) are relatively rare, with 0 occurring in December, indicating that they may be used as a preparatory tool before final assessments.

The clustering of chapter tests in the middle of the academic year suggests a structured testing schedule that prioritizes frequent formative assessments early on, while major tests appear to be administered more consistently. The presence of mock tests in December may indicate their role in preparing students for final evaluations.

This pattern highlights key periods of student assessment and suggests that the timing of tests may have implications for student performance and preparation strategies.

0.6 Power Analysis

To detect a 0.2 SD improvement in female engineering students major test scores, we conducted a power analysis using a two-sample t-test. Assuming a standard deviation of 11.1, a significance level of 5%, and 80% power, the required sample size per group is 394, with a total sample of 787. This estimate ensures sufficient power to detect a small but meaningful effect, guiding the feasibility of an intervention.
